<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880607-0109 </DOCNO><HL> Heldor Board Rejects One Acquisition Offer, Stops Seeking Others </HL><SO> </SO><CO> HDR </CO><IN> TNM </IN><DATELINE> MORRISTOWN, N.J.  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Heldor Industries Inc. said that its board rejected an acquisition offer by an investor group and that it has stopped soliciting proposals for other possible business combinations.    The maker of prefabricated pools and pool products refused to identify the suitor or disclose the amount or form of the proposal. Heldor's chief financial officer, Gerald R. Cioci, said the current book value of the company's stock is about $2.50 a share.    In American Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday, Heldor common stock closed unchanged from Friday at $2.875 a share. Based on its market price, Heldor is valued at about $10 million.    In August 1987, the company hired the investment banking firm of Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. to work out a plan to raise shareholder value, including a possible restructuring, merger or asset sale. </TEXT></DOC>